## 1. Tech Stack (fixed — do not substitute)

- **Backend:** Node.js + Express
- **Database:** MongoDB (use Mongoose for schema validation, not the raw driver)
- **Frontend dashboard:** Next.js (App Router), as a separate app from the
  Express backend — the dashboard is a client calling a standalone API, not a
  Next.js app absorbing the backend into its own API routes. Keeping them
  separate matches how this would actually be deployed (independent scaling,
  independent CORS-bounded API, swappable frontend) and avoids muddying the
  "Node.js backend" requirement with Next.js's own server runtime. Use Next.js
  here for routing/layout conventions and easy Vercel deployment, not as a
  replacement for the Express API.
  - Sessions and heatmap pages can be client components fetching from the
    Express API at runtime (`'use client'` + your API client module) — this
    data is live and per-user-session, so static generation or
    server-rendering it doesn't buy you anything here. Don't reach for
    `getServerSideProps`/server components just because Next.js offers them;
    justify the choice the same way you'd justify any other.
- **Tracking script:** Vanilla JS, zero dependencies, framework-agnostic — it must
  be embeddable in any HTML page via a single `<script>` tag, not just inside the
  React app
- **Containerization:** Docker + docker-compose for local dev (backend + mongo +
  frontend as separate services)
- **Deployment:** Frontend on Vercel, backend on Render, database on MongoDB
  Atlas (free tiers). Wire up environment variables for both environments —
  don't hardcode `localhost` URLs anywhere that would break in production.

