## 4. Tracking Script (Client Side)

This is the most "real-world" part of the assignment — treat it like a
lightweight analytics SDK, not a fetch call inside a page's `<script>` tag.

- **Single embeddable file** (`tracker.js`) with zero external dependencies,
  loadable via a plain `<script src="...">` tag on any HTML page, and exposing
  a minimal global (e.g. `window.Tracker.init({ apiUrl, ... })`) — don't make
  it depend on the demo page's own JS.
- **Session ID:** generate a UUID on first load, persist in `localStorage`
  (fall back to a cookie if localStorage is unavailable, e.g. privacy mode) so
  the session survives page navigations within the same browser session. Make
  the session expiry/lifetime a configurable constant and explain your chosen
  value (e.g. 30 minutes of inactivity = new session, which is the common
  industry default) in the README.
- **Events to capture:**
  - `page_view` — fired once on script init / page load, capturing `page_url`.
  - `click` — fired on every click anywhere on the document, capturing
    `x`/`y` (use `event.pageX`/`pageY`, not `clientX`/`clientY`, so
    coordinates are consistent regardless of scroll position — note this
    distinction in code comments since it's a common bug), plus current
    viewport dimensions.
- **Batching/queueing (this is the key architectural requirement):**
  - Don't fire a network request per event. Push events into an in-memory
    queue and flush it:
    - every N seconds (e.g. 5s) via `setInterval`, AND
    - immediately if the queue reaches a max size (e.g. 10 events), AND
    - on page unload/visibility change, using `navigator.sendBeacon()` (not
      `fetch`) for the final flush — `sendBeacon` is the correct browser API
      for this because it guarantees delivery without blocking unload, which
      `fetch` does not.
  - Explain in a code comment why `sendBeacon` is used specifically for the
    unload case vs. the interval case (where a normal `fetch` is fine).
- **Resilience:** if a batch POST fails (network error, server 5xx), re-queue
  the events for the next flush attempt rather than silently dropping them;
  cap retries/queue growth so a dead backend doesn't leak memory on a
  long-lived tab.
- **Non-blocking:** the script must never throw an uncaught error that breaks
  the host page — wrap tracking logic in try/catch so a tracking bug can't
  take down the site it's embedded in. This is a real constraint production
  analytics SDKs (Segment, GA, etc.) all have to honor.

### Demo page
Build one simple static HTML page (a few buttons/links/sections to click on)
that includes `tracker.js` via a script tag, purely to generate realistic test
data for the dashboard.

