## 5. Dashboard (Next.js)

### Sessions View
- Table of all sessions: session_id (truncated/copyable), event count,
  first_seen, last_seen, pages_visited. Paginated, matching the backend's
  pagination.
- Clicking a session row navigates to (or expands into) the ordered event
  journey: a vertical timeline-style list showing each event in order
  (icon/label for `page_view` vs `click`, timestamp, page URL, and x/y for
  clicks).

### Heatmap View
- Dropdown (populated from `GET /api/pages`) to select a page URL.
- Render click positions as dots overlaid on a representative container sized
  to a reference viewport — scale stored `x`/`y` by the ratio of the stored
  `viewport_width`/`height` to the rendering container's actual size, so
  points line up sensibly even if clicks were captured at different screen
  sizes. A simple semi-transparent radial dot per click is sufficient; a true
  density gradient is a nice-to-have, not required.
- Handle the empty state (no clicks for selected page) explicitly.

### General frontend concerns
- Centralize API calls in one small client module (don't scatter raw `fetch`
  calls through components); read the API base URL from
  `process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL` so the same build works against
  localhost and the deployed backend, and document the `NEXT_PUBLIC_` prefix
  requirement (anything without it is server-only and won't reach the
  browser bundle).
- Use the App Router's file-based routing for the two views (e.g.
  `/sessions`, `/sessions/[sessionId]`, `/heatmap`) instead of client-side
  tab-switching in one page — this gives you real shareable URLs for each
  view, which is a small but real production win over a single-page SPA.
- Loading and error states for every data fetch — don't let the dashboard
  show a blank screen while data loads or silently fail on an API error.

